name: Madoka and Strange Thoughts
description:
Madoka is a very strange girl, and therefore she suddenly wondered how many
pairs of integers 
    (a, b)
 exist, where 
    1 
    ≤ a, b 
    ≤ n
, for
which 
    lcm(a, b)/
    gcd(a, b)
    ≤ 3
. In this problem, 
    gcd(a, b)
 denotes the
greatest common divisor of the numbers 
    a
 and 
    b
, and

    lcm(a, b)
 denotes the smallest common multiple of the
numbers 
    a
 and 
    b
. Input The input consists of multiple test cases.
The first line contains a single integer 
    t
 (
    1 
    ≤ t 
    ≤ 10^4
)
— the number of test cases. Description of the test cases follows. The first
and the only line of each test case contains the integer 
    n
 (
    1 
    ≤ n
    
    ≤ 10^8
). Output For each test case output a single integer — the number
of pairs of integers satisfying the condition. Example Input 6 1 2 3 4 5
100000000 Output 1 4 7 10 11 266666666 Note For 
    n = 1
 there is exactly
one pair of numbers — 
    (1, 1)
 and it fits. For 
    n = 2
, there are
only 
    4
 pairs — 
    (1, 1)
, 
    (1, 2)
, 
    (2, 1)
, 
    (2, 2)

and they all fit. For 
    n = 3
, all 
    9
 pair are suitable, except

    (2, 3)
 and 
    (3, 2)
, since their 
    lcm
 is

    6
, and 
    gcd
 is 
    1
, which doesn't fit the
condition.
